('1',	'1',	'',	'',	'',	'',	'',	0,	'',	'',	'',	'l',	0,	'Here Comes the Sun',	'ENHANCE,THE WEST QUAD',	'nstallations on the Village Inn and, most recently, on the Village Market are advancing Kenyon in its goal of achieving carbon neutrality â€” all while helping students learn the ins and outs of the solar power industry.\r\nThe solar power installations were designed and implemented by students inÂ â€œSolar Power Systems: Science, Policy and Practicum,â€Â a physics course co-taught by Assistant Professor of Physics and Scientific Computing Eric Holdener and veteran solar power consultant Jerry Kelly â€™96. The course teaches students about the process of proposing, designing and installing a solar power project, while also raising public awareness of the viability of renewable energy.\r\nâ€œItâ€™s a good gateway to be introduced to the solar industry,â€ said Lufeng May Chen â€™20, from Shanghai, China, one of 16 students who took the course during the fall 2017 semester.\r\nAbout the Class\r\nThe class attracts students from all majors and across all class years. Holdener and Kelly guide students through the basic physics of electricity and photovoltaics, as well as basic electrical circuitry. They incorporate fieldwork throughout the semester, traveling with the students to visit Knox County residents who already own solar installations. Students also learn from guest speakers in the solar industry â€” including Zach Sawicki â€™16, a political science major who took the original version of the course and now works for a renewable energy development company in nearby Columbus.\r\nâ€œWe give the class exposure to people who have gotten into this field by any number of routes, and we show them how it can be done,â€ Holdener said.\r\nâ€œA lot of the new hires in most solar companies in the U.S. now are coming in with little technical knowledge of solar,â€ Kelly added. â€œCompanies are spending a lot of money and effort to train them. This class gets the students over that initial learning curve of knowing what the technology is, knowing what it can and canâ€™t do, how systems are best located and how theyâ€™re constructed. We think it will give them an advantage if they pursue a career in renewable energy.â€\r\n\r\n\r\nWe give the class exposure to people who have gotten into this field by any number of routes, and we show them how it can be done.\r\n\r\n- ERIC HOLDENER, ASSISTANT PROFESSOR OF PHYSICS &amp; SCIENTIFIC COMPUTING\r\n\r\nStudents also learn about different financial aspects of the renewable energy field and the factors that people typically weigh when considering whether to install solar panels. For Frances Matthews â€™18, an economics major from Bracknell, England, the class provided an opportunity to apply lessons from her economics classes and help her classmates analyze the costs and benefits of solar installations.\r\n\r\nWe give the class exposure to people who have gotten into this field by any number of routes, and we show them how it can be done.\r\n\r\nâ€œAnalyzing the business side and cost structures in solar has helped demonstrate the complexities of the industry&quot;\r\nThe Results\r\nAt the end of the semester, students pitch ideas for future solar installations on Kenyonâ€™s campus to Chief Business Officer Mark Kohlman. To develop their proposals, students conduct site evaluations, measuring a siteâ€™s available unshaded space as well as its typical electricity usage. They create a preliminary design for their proposed installation and discuss design challenges, including any factors that may increase the cost of the project. The course culminates in a â€œflip-the-switchâ€ ceremony, when the students officially power up the solar installation proposed and designed by their predecessors in the class.\r\nEnrollment in the course is one of many ways to participate in Kenyonâ€™s green initiatives. â€œKenyon is a great place to come if you want more of a hands-on experience in sustainability,â€ Matthews said. â€œThereâ€™s sustainable agriculture, you can get involved at the BFEC and thereâ€™s a living cemetery down the road. There are so many ways to get hands-on with the environment because we are fortunate enough to be surrounded by the environment and the countryside.â€',	'http://fastspot.loc/files/modules/65c42c856f66f1129c6f4285578b7c09-2-3.jpg',	'',	''),
